am just roleplaying my evil character&quot;</P><P>As one who loves to play evil as well as good (no my name above is not my evil characters name), it offends me and the entire RPG gendre that so many ppl haven't got a clue as to what it means to role play a truly evil character.</P><P>There is a very thin line between being truly evil and being a jerk.  Turning ppl invis to block hallways is just being a jerk hiding behind your evil race.</P><P>On a game called the Realm (by Sierra at the time) my evil character was well known and hated by all, both good guilds and evil guilds.  My goal was to get on every guild hit list but I was never jerk.  I never misled on who I was,  hid myself behind invisability or use offensive language.  Yet, I was a very dark character that all hated.  When you can do that then you will understand what being evil is all about.</font></td></tr><tr><td bgcolor='#6F6559' valign="top"><font color='#ffffff' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Godspeed</font></td><td bgcolor='#6F6559'  valign='top' ><font color='#ffffff' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='1'>Posted - 4 December 2000 11:54 PST</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="Javascript:openWindow('profile.asp?mode=display&id=23293')"><img src='profile.gif' alt='Show Profile' border=0 align='absmiddle' hspace=6></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href='mail.asp?id=23293'><img src='email.gif' alt='Email Poster' border=0 align='absmiddle' hspace=6></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href='post.asp?method=edit&reply_id=153423&auth=23293&forum_title=EQ+Tavern&topic_title=Comments%3A+%28PHOF%29+%2D+Not+an+RPG&forum_id=1315&topic_id=28807'><img src='edit.gif' alt='Edit Message' border=0 align='absmiddle' hspace=6></a><hr noshade size=1><font color='#ffffff' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>I agree with Inspiration on many things. Role-playing, for example, doesn't consist of just (or mainly) killing other people's characters. If you play or have been playing D&amp;D, think about how many other characters you were able to kill (not npc's) before the other people whacked you or the DM put a leash on you. I myself have also played D&amp;D for years, as well as other games of the fantasy genre. I'm not saying that what I say is justified or absolutely correct, only my opinion. I am saying that experience doesn't matter, it's how you play the game. I've met plenty of newbies who were very good role-players, and I've met some I'd like to 'blast out of their muddy boots' - to take a phrase from the text-based RPG Gemstone III. Back to the point, I've played with someone who liked to ALWAYS play the bad guy, and stir up trouble for us - the group. Little time was spent causing trouble for the npc's. I literally HATED to play with him, and so did everyone else. His D&amp;D group changed so many times it's pitiful. I've also played with a guy who loved to play chaotic and crazy characters, but the way in which he played made it fun for everyone. I'm not saying that he didn't cause some friction for the party, but it was always fun. His role-play was both intelligent and enjoyable. My point is, don't try, but BE considerate of those around you who are trying to have a good time as well. After all, that's what we're doing when we're on EQ, right? If you people keep trying to stir up more junk for the rest of us then all you're doing is adding those elements that already exist in the real world, hate and greed. As far as your comment, bubba, I'll assume that by your logic baseball, football, basketball players and every sport nut in the world is just a kid who won't grow up, either. We 'play' sports since we're kids and when we get older we whine about not getting paid $10 million a year to keep 'playing,' but we can't role 'play' just for fun, because it's a kid thing? Hmm. . .I really don't think it's worth my time to post any more on that topic. I suggest for your sake you go to another board. What are you doing on this one, anyway, if that's your opinion? I'm confused.</P><P>Godspeed</P><P>&quot;A fool speaks and then reflects, a wise man reflects, and then speaks.&quot;</font></td></tr><tr><td bgcolor='#6F6559' valign="top"><font color='#ffffff' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Raxian</font></td><td bgcolor='#6F6559'  valign='top' ><font color='#ffffff' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='1'>Posted - 15 June 2001 14:44 PST</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="Javascript:openWindow('profile.asp?mode=display&id=38043')"><img src='profile.gif' alt='Show Profile' border=0 align='absmiddle' hspace=6></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href='mail.asp?id=38043'><img src='email.gif' alt='Email Poster' border=0 align='absmiddle' hspace=6></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href='post.asp?method=edit&reply_id=204005&auth=38043&forum_title=EQ+Tavern&topic_title=Comments%3A+%28PHOF%29+%2D+Not+an+RPG&forum_id=1315&topic_id=28807'><img src='edit.gif' alt='Edit Message' border=0 align='absmiddle' hspace=6></a><hr noshade size=1><font color='#ffffff' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Greetings! I would call Everquest and most games like it ...FPG Fantasy Playing Games. More specific to seperate it from the RPG genre, without isolating it as a &quot;hack and booty&quot; game, since there is more to it. I love Role Playing myself...wether its Conversing with a Innkeeper or risking life and limb.  Games are fun, especially those that challenge you, make you think, react, then act, peek your imagination and creativity...</P><P>I used to belong to a game called Meridian 59 (I am not sure if any of you remember or have even heard of that...by 3do) it was a good game, at first...but PK was rampant (no choice of pvp and non-pvp...and it ruined the game. I was a guide on that and I had to leave because it was just to much to deal with...what a waste to. Story line and world was pretty good. Many different sources of magic and such to learn. But I would consider this FPG as well...(well as I guide I did more RPG then FPG) I like the game, and the graphics are cool, etc, etc....it is difficult to roleplay when you have to spend time makeing money and hunt all time. </font></td></tr>

